Of course, this is a very fascinating question dealing with rational functions! We notice that we are given that, \[56x+33y = \frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}, \qquad (1)\] and \[33x-56y = \frac{x}{x^2+y^2}, \qquad (2)\] and we wish to determine the value of $|x|+|y|$. Adding and subtracting $(1)$ and $(2)$ we get, \begin{align*}
49x & = \frac{-y+x}{x^2+y^2}, \\
-23y & = \frac{x+y}{x^2+y^2}.
\end{align*} (3) and (4) We write the equations in the form, \begin{align*}
49x(x^2+y^2) = -y+x, \\ 
-23y(x^2+y^2) = x+y.
\end{align*} (5) Since $x^2+y^2 = |z|^2$, where $z=x+yi$, we get, \[|z|(102y+49x) = x-y, \qquad (6)\] and \[|z|(49x-102y) = x+y=|z|(|x|-|y|) \qquad (7)\] Adding $(6)$ and $(7)$ we get \[(102x)|z| = 2|x|, \qquad \text{so} \qquad |z| = \frac{1}{51}. \qquad (8)\]
Now using $(7)$, we have \[|z|^2 = 1-102|z|\left(\frac{x}{|z|}\right) = 1-2x = 1-2y, \qquad (9)\] \[|z|^2 = 1+102|z|\left(\frac{y}{|z|}\right) = 1-2y = 1+2x. \qquad (10)\] Combining $(9)$ and $(10)$ we get \[1-2x = 1+2y, \] and so \begin{align*}
x & = -y \\
& = \pm \frac{1}{3\sqrt{57}}.
\end{align*} So $|x|+|y|$ lies in $\sqrt{\frac{408}{3245}} = \boxed{\frac{4 \sqrt{6}}{51}}. ~\blacksquare$

Sincegcd$\left(33,56\right)=1$ and $33^2+56^2$ is a perfect square, which number other than $33$ should be my hint? To get $56$something we could try to switch order of $33$ and $56$. So switch order of $33$ and $56$ in both equations: \begin{align*} 
33x-56y&=-\tfrac xy \\
56x+33y&=\tfrac x {x^2+y^2}
\end{align*}
This isn't elegant but it does work. We turn it into rational curves:
\begin{align*}
y&=-\frac{-\tfrac xy-56x}{33}\\
y&=\frac{x}{\frac x {56} - 33y}
\end{align*}
clearing the denominators yields
\begin{align}
33yx^2+y^2&=56x^2 \\
-11856x^3+33y^3&=x^2+y^2 \Rightarrow y^3-12x^3=0
\end{align}
We could divide by $y^3$ to get the elliptic curve proposed by ltfnu.

